Lieutenant-General Fannie Masemola is South Africa's new national police commissioner. Masemola takes over from General Khehla Sitole. President Cyril Ramaphosa made the announcement on Thursday. eNCA's Shahan Ramkisoon spoke to DA’s Andrew Whitfield about the appointment. JOHANNESBURG - The Democratic Alliance has welcomed the appointment of Lieutenant-General Fannie Masemola as the new national police commissioner. The party also says it’s concerned by the process leading to the appointment. READ: Ramaphosa announces new National Commissioner of Police It says the involvement of Police Minister Bheki Cele is worrying. The DA's Andrew Whitfield said, “it’s welcomed that we have a new police commissioner who has come up through the ranks who has served in senior management." "The key problem here is the process which was followed. This process was presided over by Bheki Cele who we believe to be at the heart of the problem within the South African police services." "Masemola needs to show he’s independent and deliver results. It doesn’t matter who is appointed. We’re extremely concerned about the minister’s hand in this process.’